ce:section.ce:para:
Reactive oxygen species (ROS) are the by-products of cellular metabolism, including singlet oxygen (1O2), free radicals (hydroperoxyl (HO2
                     ), hydroxyl (OH), and superoxide (O2

                     −)). Oxidative stress occurs when the generation of ROS exceeds the anti-oxidant capacity of cellular anti-oxidants in a biological system, leading to oxidative damage to lipids, proteins, and DNA [4]. Some CDs have been shown to generate ROS that point toward their potential use in photodynamic therapy (PDT) [5,6], serving as photosensitizers (PS) to kill tumor or microbial cells upon photoexcitation [4,7,8]. Red-emission CDs obtain increasing appreciation, because of their ability to penetrate deeper into a cell and thus reduce noise signal. According to the latest reports [9], the addition of conjugated structures in CDs can make the emission shift towards red wavelengths [10–15]. Porphyrin is a natural aromatic macrocyclic compound with 18 π-electrons, containing four methines and four pyrrole rings. It is an indispensable natural macromolecular ligand in biological activities, and involved in cell respiration, detoxification of exogenous substances, oxygen transport, fatty acid oxidation, photosynthesis and among other functions. In addition, the fact that most porphyrin structures emit deep penetrating red fluorescence makes them a promising candidate for bioimaging [16–19]. Cancer is among the deadliest diseases [20], and their diagnosis in early stage remains the major bottleneck for its prognosis. Biocompatibility and therapeutic efficiency are most important issues in the design of ideal anticancer nanomedicines. Among numerous theranostic nanoplatforms, protein-based nanocarriers with an inherent biocompatibility have been applied extensively in cancer therapy [21–24]. Ferritin is the main protein containing iron in humans and most mammals. It consists of 24 subunits, and there are natural cavities in their spatial structures, thereby forming a nanometer cage structure with an outer diameter of 12 nm and an inner diameter of 8 nm [25,26]. Ferritin has been used to synthesize inorganic nanoparticles in macromolecular protein nanoreactors [27]. Transferrin (Trf) attached nanostructure is highly targeted due to the presence of Trf receptors on the surface of some cells, e.g., Bend.3 cells, which can specifically bind to Trf. This helps nanocomposites enter cells and enrich in cell interior through endocytosis, thereby improving the efficiency of the nanodrug.
